@leaboberg is part of a small but sharp wave of designers reworking Savile Row tailoring into something looser, stranger, and more alive. The London-based label twists classic suiting with roomy blazers built for movement and raw-edged lapels that fray further over time, giving formalwear an intentionally undone edge. Usually made-to-measure from the brand’s atelier, Boberg’s ready-to-wear pieces have been notoriously hard to track down outside Asia, with only a handful of stockists like New York’s Ven.Space and Vancouver’s Neighbour carrying the line.⁠
⁠
Now, Boberg is widening access with “Issue 01,” a capsule made from leftover British and Japanese fabrics sourced from past seasons. Available directly through the brand’s website, the collection includes signature oversized blazers like the close-buttoned RPL and the single-breasted RNL, alongside slouchy trousers, draped shirts, and ties cut from deadstock wool. It’s a softer, more relaxed vision of tailoring that trades Savile Row rigidity for ease, volume, and movement.

@JacobAndCo. unveils the Godfather II, a $440,000 musical timepiece that brings cinema to the wrist.
Drawing inspiration from one of film’s most iconic sagas, the watch integrates two legendary compositions — The Godfather’s Waltz and The Godfather Love Theme — played through an intricate, built-in music box.
Encased in a sculpted Art Deco-inspired design, the piece combines horological artistry with cinematic storytelling. A flying tourbillon, dual power reserves, and a newly engineered movement elevate both its technical and aesthetic appeal, while the dial features a finely detailed portrait of Don Corleone alongside subtle references to the film’s legacy.
Limited to just 74 pieces, in tribute to the 1974 release of The Godfather Part II, the timepiece stands as a rare collector’s creation, where music, craftsmanship, and heritage converge.
